<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="survey-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Create quantitative instruments that yield valid data. Conduct 10+ interviews first; questions must be specific, single-concept, and neutral; fail if hypotheticals or exceed 7 minutes.</summary>
    <category>research</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>survey</tag>
      <tag>quantitative-research</tag>
      <tag>questionnaire-design</tag>
      <tag>user-research</tag>
      <tag>data-collection</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Survey Design</title>
    <summary>Survey design is the methodology for creating quantitative research instruments that yield valid, actionable data. The core rule: conduct at least 10 interviews before building a survey — surveys quantify known patterns, they cannot discover unknown problems. Every question must be specific, single-concept, and neutrally worded; surveys fail when they ask hypotheticals instead of facts or exceed 7 minutes in length.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Surveys without methodology training produce misleading data. Leading questions bias responses, double-barreled items confuse respondents, hypothetical questions over-predict intent by 2-5x, and self-selection on distribution channels distorts the sample. Systematic design eliminates these failure modes before fielding.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>After 10+ qualitative interviews have surfaced patterns worth quantifying</item>
        <item>Pricing sensitivity studies (Van Westendorp, Gabor-Granger) where N >= 100 is realistic</item>
        <item>Feature prioritization across an installed user base (MaxDiff, Kano, importance/satisfaction matrix)</item>
        <item>Periodic NPS/CSAT tracking against a stable cohort</item>
        <item>Screener-driven recruitment funnels for follow-up interviews</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Discovery of unknown problems — interviews and observation reveal what surveys cannot ask about</item>
        <item>Sample sizes below ~30 — stick to interviews; quantitative claims are not defensible</item>
        <item>Predicting future behavior ("would you pay X?") — use price-anchored conjoint or pre-orders</item>
        <item>B2B segments where the named buyer is gated — 1:1 outreach beats panel surveys</item>
        <item>Internal stakeholder alignment — use a workshop, not a survey</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="design-process">
      <p>Six-step process for creating surveys that yield valid, actionable quantitative data.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Conduct at least 10 qualitative interviews before creating a survey.</statement>
        <rationale>Surveys quantify known patterns; they cannot discover unknown problems. Without prior interviews, you cannot write valid questions — you do not yet know what to ask.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="step-1-research-objective">
        <rule>
          <statement>Define one specific research question, the decision it informs, the target audience, and a minimum sample size before writing a single survey question.</statement>
          <rationale>Surveys without a defined objective drift toward vague data that cannot drive any decision. A crisp objective statement also prevents scope creep during question writing.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/survey-design-doc.md">Survey design document template with objective section</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="step-2-question-types">
        <p>Select the question type that best fits each research goal:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Multiple choice: discrete, mutually exclusive options ("How often do you...?")</item>
          <item>Rating scale (5-point general, 7-point nuanced, 10-point NPS, binary yes/no)</item>
          <item>Ranking: priority order across 3-7 items</item>
          <item>Open-ended: one or two per survey maximum, placed at the end</item>
          <item>Matrix: multiple items against the same scale (satisfaction across features)</item>
          <item>NPS (0-10): loyalty and recommendation intent only</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="step-3-write-questions">
        <rule>
          <statement>Each question must be specific, single-concept, neutrally worded, and answerable from direct experience — not hypothetical intent.</statement>
          <rationale>Double-barreled items ("How easy and useful is X?") split respondent attention and make data uninterpretable. Hypothetical questions ("Would you pay X?") over-predict actual behavior by 2-5x.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <example type="bad">
          <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Bad: "How often will you use this feature?"
Why: hypothetical future intent, not past behavior
Bad: "How satisfied and engaged are you?"
Why: double-barreled — two separate questions fused
Bad: "Don't you think X is better than Y?"
Why: leading — presupposes a preferred answer]]></code>
        </example>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Good: "How often have you used similar tools in the last 30 days?"
Good: "How satisfied are you with [product]?" + separate "How engaged do you feel?"
Good: "Which do you prefer, X or Y?"]]></code>
        </example>
        <reference path="templates/question-bank.md">Per-research-type question banks (pricing, satisfaction, feature prioritization)</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="step-4-structure-survey">
        <rule>
          <statement>Keep total completion time under 7 minutes; longer surveys drop below 50% completion. Place screener first, demographics last, open-ended questions at the end.</statement>
          <rationale>Completion rates drop sharply past 7 minutes. Screener questions at the front disqualify off-target respondents before they waste time on core questions. Demographics last reduces abandonment from privacy-sensitive openers.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Screener (1-2 questions): qualify respondents, route off-target out</item>
          <item>Attention check at Q5: "Select 'Somewhat agree' to confirm you are reading"</item>
          <item>Easy warm-up (2-3 questions): build momentum</item>
          <item>Core questions (5-10): main research objective</item>
          <item>Demographics (3-5): segmentation variables</item>
          <item>Open-ended (1-2): additional context, never more</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="step-5-test-and-distribute">
        <rule>
          <statement>Pilot with 5-10 people from the actual audience and measure median completion time. If median exceeds 7 minutes, cut questions until it does not.</statement>
          <rationale>Self-estimated completion time is always optimistic. Piloting reveals confusing items, technical issues, and timing reality before the main field period.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Distribution channel trade-offs: email list (qualified but biased to existing users), social media (broad reach but self-selection), paid panels (fast and targeted but expensive and variable quality), in-product (high completion but only active users), communities (engaged and specific but may be small).</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>For paid panels, do not let an agent auto-launch fielding — cost spikes and ethics review require a human approval gate.</statement>
          <rationale>Automated panel launches can incur significant unexpected costs and may violate panel provider terms if attention-check criteria are not pre-configured.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="step-6-analyze-results">
        <rule>
          <statement>Deduplicate on (IP, device fingerprint, completion time &lt; 30% of median) before any analysis. Paid panels return 5-30% bot or satisficer responses.</statement>
          <rationale>Drawing conclusions from unfiltered panel data overstates real market preferences and invalidates statistical significance claims.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Quantitative: response distributions, cross-tabulations by segment, statistical significance</item>
          <item>Qualitative (open-ended): theme coding with counts, verbatim quotes per theme required</item>
          <item>Report open-ended analysis with the actual corpus size explicitly stated</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="question-writing-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Randomize answer-option order on every multiple-choice and matrix item (except scales, where order is meaningful).</statement>
        <rationale>First-option bias inflates selection of the top-listed answer by 5-15% in self-administered surveys.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>For pricing, never ask "would you pay X." Use Van Westendorp (4 price-sensitivity questions) plus a real price anchor or a pre-order page.</statement>
        <rationale>Stated willingness-to-pay is 2-5x higher than actual purchase behavior. Behavioral anchors (price anchoring, actual payment) produce calibrated estimates.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Anchor sample size to the decision, not vanity. For a directional preference split at 95% CI with ±10pp precision, n=100 per segment is sufficient.</statement>
        <rationale>Collecting 1,000 responses when 100 answer the question wastes fielding budget and adds no precision to the key decision metric.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Segment in the analysis plan before fielding. Do not slice by unplanned variables post-hoc without flagging the analysis as exploratory.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-hoc segmentation inflates false-positive rates by increasing the number of comparisons tested on the same data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Version-control the survey JSON alongside the analysis notebook. Surveys are code.</statement>
        <rationale>Undocumented survey changes between waves make longitudinal comparisons invalid and findings unreproducible.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading questions that presuppose an answer ("Don't you think X is better?")</description>
        <reason>Biases responses toward the implied preferred answer; data cannot be used for unbiased inference.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Surveys with no screener questions at the front</description>
        <reason>Off-target respondents contaminate the sample; results apply to an undefined population.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Only closed questions with no open-ended field</description>
        <reason>Misses unknown motivations and verbatim language that reveals how respondents actually think about the problem.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Quantitative claims from samples below 100</description>
        <reason>Confidence intervals are too wide for actionable decision-making; switch to qualitative interviews instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No pilot test before full distribution</description>
        <reason>Confusing questions, broken logic, and unexpected completion times only surface in the pilot; fixing post-field is impossible.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Run bias-linter.py on every agent-drafted question set before sending to human review. Agents drift toward double-barrel items ("How easy and intuitive is...") and leading framings that they then rationalize away.</statement>
        <rationale>Regex-based deterministic checks catch patterns the LLM rationalizes as acceptable when reviewing its own output.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/bias-linter.py">Python pre-filter detecting leading, hypothetical, absolutist, and double-barrel questions</reference>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents use Likert-5 for everything without justifying scale choice per question</description>
        <reason>Scale choice affects response distribution; 5-point scales compress nuance for attitude items where 7-point is standard.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-generated demographics duplicate or omit segments tracked in user-personas.md</description>
        <reason>Mismatched demographic options prevent cross-study comparison; always pass the personas doc as context and require options to be a subset.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent summarizes open-ended fields without disclosing how many responses were actually read</description>
        <reason>Silent corpus truncation produces hallucinated synthesis that looks like full-corpus analysis.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/survey-design-doc.md" purpose="Full survey design document template with objective, screener, core questions, demographics, and distribution plan"/>
      <template path="templates/question-bank.md" purpose="Per-research-type question banks: pricing (Van Westendorp), satisfaction (NPS/matrix), feature prioritization (MaxDiff)"/>
      <template path="templates/bias-linter.py" purpose="Python pre-filter that detects leading, hypothetical, absolutist, and double-barrel questions before LLM review"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
